00:50.078 --> 01:00.430
now about the conversion or changes in the field of 
veterinary medicine, say, in the Southwest, in

00:50.078 --> 01:00.430
Texas. moving, essentially, from the large 
animal rural production orientation to

01:01.287 --> 01:08.217
something else. And I don't want to put words in 
your mouth, but just sort of give us an image of how

01:08.237 --> 01:14.406
things have changed. Of course, it follows the 
trend of people. We were an agrarian society. I

01:23.499 --> 01:25.862
grew up in the agrarian society. My daddy was a 
little patch farmer, geeked out a living. turning

01:31.645 --> 01:36.272
the soil, and we had animals, and we respected the 
animals. The animals worked for us, and if we cared

01:36.292 --> 01:46.127
for the animals, they'd do the work for us, and they 
were important to us, and we had them to eat. We had

01:46.147 --> 01:50.614
hogs, and we killed hogs, and we killed calves, and 
all that, and we ate them. Right over the farm, we

01:50.634 --> 01:54.040
didn't go out and buy the reef or pork. That was 
produced right there on the farm, and... Animals

01:59.759 --> 02:02.081
were very important out there. And there was a need 
for the care of those animals. The veterinarian's

02:08.127 --> 02:15.174
lifestyle then was individual animal treatment. 
Pure and simple. The old cow got sick, and he was

02:16.256 --> 02:24.624
called to treat the old cow.

02:24.644 --> 02:27.607
The dog wasn't as fortunate. He could go. He 
usually didn't. They didn't even call the

02:30.353 --> 02:33.838
veterinarian for a dog or take him to the 
veterinarian either. But the dog was an essential

02:34.820 --> 02:40.969
utilitarian animal around the place, but you can 
get more dogs very fast. And so he wasn't as

02:42.230 --> 02:45.335
important. Oh, we had his pets, yeah, but mostly 
they were utilitarian. They didn't come in the

02:49.661 --> 02:53.627
house and we didn't pet them like we do today.

02:56.780 --> 02:59.845
that I thought the world of when I was a kid. Little 
squirrel dogs and things. I found a lot of

03:02.169 --> 03:04.673
squirrels. Highly utilitarian. You bet. And 
sheepdogs and all those, you know, that handle

03:07.597 --> 03:12.064
little goats and herd them. But the dog was a dog. 
And a lot of people, and they had no rights. But we

03:21.079 --> 03:22.882
treated them nicely. We fed them carefully. care 
of them and gave them a good place to sleep and all

03:24.792 --> 03:28.696
that. Tried to treat them right. And as a kid we were 
taught that. Well, people began to move to the

03:35.422 --> 03:41.608
town. You know, urbanization took place and 
country people moved to town. And country people

03:46.213 --> 03:52.819
had been related to animals out there in the 
country. And they got into town and concrete

03:54.965 --> 03:59.571
jungles, and those animals weren't there, and 
they missed those animals. They longed for those

04:00.773 --> 04:03.096
animals. So they began slowly to take in pets. Now 
these are really pets then, you see. They're not

04:10.426 --> 04:13.290
really utilitarian, but they're pets. They're 
satisfying the emotions of people rather than the

04:13.650 --> 04:19.418
economics of people. So it went from economics to 
emotional. And pets now are emotional

04:23.315 --> 04:30.462
characters.

04:30.482 --> 04:40.993
So the small animal practice then began to come on 
the picture, all for what people wanted. Now, all

04:41.013 --> 04:49.862
the time and all the way through, it has been bound 
by what people

04:41.013 --> 04:49.862
wanted. Sometimes in committees and groups that 
are surveying and evaluating the veterinary

04:51.968 --> 05:16.335
medical profession, it's easy for those in the 
